Variable = a container for a value. Behaves as the value that it contains

Checking a datatype: 
	print(type(name))
Converting a datatype: 
	type casting - convert the data type of a value to another data type
	Temporary change = print(int(y))
	Permanent change y=2.0,y=int(y) 
	Str(age) converts age from an int to a string
	
String:
	Series of Characters
	Use '' or ""
	Example: 
	
	name="Bro"
	print(name) 
	
	name="Bro"
	print("Hello "+name)
	
	#first_name="Joshua"
	#last_name="Rickson"
	#full_name=first_name+""+last_name
	#print("Hello"+first_name+",Howareyou?")
	#print("Hello"+full_name)
	
Int:
	Number (No quotes)
	
	#age=21
	#age=age+1
	#age+=1
	#print(age)
	#print("Yourageis:"+str(age))
	
Float:
	Floating point number (a decimal number)
	
	#height=250.55
	
Boolean:
	(True or False) REQUIRES CAPITAL
	
	#human=False
	#print(human)
	
Scope = The region that a variable is recognized
		A variable is only available from inside the region it is created
		A global and locally scoped versions of a variable can be created

def display_name():
    name = "Rickson" #local scope (avail only inside the function)
    print(name)

	- Local
	- Enclosing
	- Global
	- Built-In
